{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17517765","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17517765"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:56:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:56:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12834"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12834","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12834"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.29,0.25,0.05,0.36,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5277"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110685"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5277","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5277"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12834"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92933"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"3543"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"9735"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8982"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9460"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15771"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41746"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41767"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42822"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43355"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110685","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110685"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 26-year-old woman presents to the clinic with a two month history of palpitations, headache and insomnia. She has also had mild diarrhoea and some weight loss, despite an increase in her appetite. Three months ago she gave birth to a baby boy after an uneventful pregnancy and delivery. She is otherwise in good health, with no medical history of note and does not take any medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination her blood pressure is 135/95 mmHg, pulse 98/min and temperature 37.3\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. The rest of the examination is unremarkable, apart from a non-tender, firm and slightly enlarged thyroid gland. Her laboratory investigation show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EESR: 10mm/hr (0-30)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECRP: 2.3mg/L (\u0026lt;5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHb: 134g/L\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELeucocytes: 6.7 x 10^9 cells/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ET4: 50pmol/L (10-20)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ET3: 8.5pmol/L (3.1-5.4)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETSH: 0.1mIU/L (0.4-4.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum thyroid peroxidase antibodies: 104 IU/mL(\u0026lt;35)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Conservative management","Propylthiouracil","Levothyroxine","Carbimazole","Radioactive iodine"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient in this scenario has presented with a classical case of postpartum thyroiditis. Postpartum thyroiditis typically occurs within 1 year postpartum, and occurs in three phases: phase 1 results in hyperthyroidism due to the release of preformed thyroid hormones; phase 2 results in hypothyroidism which can last for up to 12 months, and requires levothyroxine; and phase 3 in which thyroid function returns to normal. Not all patients will experience phase 2. This diagnosis is supported by the onset of symptoms and biochemical findings. Postpartum thyroiditis is caused by lymphocytic infiltration of the thyroid gland within the first few months of delivery. During the hyperthyroid phase, \u003Cstrong\u003Econservative management \u003C/strong\u003Eis all that is warranted because in the vast majority it is self-limiting disease. Symptomatic control can be achieved with beta-blockade.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPropylthiouracil \u003C/strong\u003Eand \u003Cstrong\u003Ecarbimazole \u003C/strong\u003Eare antithyroid drugs that can be used for treating hyperthyroidism in patients with Graves\u0027 disease. They do not have a role in postpartum thyroiditis because the hormones are already preformed, and not over-produced as occurs in conditions like Graves\u0027 whereby treatment with antithyroid drugs is warranted.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELevothyroxine\u003C/strong\u003E is required during the hypothyroid phase of postpartum thyroiditis, but right now the patient is in the hyperthyroid state, and this can exacerbate the condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERadioactive iodine \u003C/strong\u003Etreats by destroying the thyroid tissue, but it is not indicated in postpartum thyroiditis because of the self-limiting nature of the disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Conservative management is the treatment of choice for patients with postpartum thyroiditis."],"references":["Naji Rad S, Deluxe L. Postpartum Thyroiditis. [Updated 2022 Jun 21]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557646/","Pearce EN, Farwell AP, Braverman LE. Thyroiditis. N Engl J Med. 2003 Jun 26;348(26):2646-55. doi: 10.1056/NEJMra021194. Erratum in: N Engl J Med. 2003 Aug 7;349(6):620. PMID: 12826640."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92933"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12834"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92933","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92933"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-03T10:53:58+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-03T10:54:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5277"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110685"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.